<text>In mathematics a polydivisible number (or magic number) is a number in a given number base with digits &quot;abcde...&quot; that has the following properties:

# Its first digit &quot;a&quot; is not 0.
# The number formed by its first two digits &quot;ab&quot; is a multiple of 2.
# The number formed by its first three digits &quot;abc&quot; is a multiple of 3.
# The number formed by its first four digits &quot;abcd&quot; is a multiple of 4.
# etc.

==Definition==
Let formula_1 be a positive integer, and let formula_2 be the number of digits in &quot;n&quot; written in base &quot;b&quot;. The number &quot;n&quot; is a polydivisible number if for all formula_3,
: formula_4. 

; Example

For example, 10801 is a seven-digit polydivisible number in base 4, as 
: formula_5
: formula_6
: formula_7
: formula_8
: formula_9
: formula_10
: formula_11

==Enumeration==
For any given base formula_12, there are only a finite number of polydivisible numbers.

